  "title": "Resolving the Paradox of Clumped Seed Dispersal: Positive Density and Distance Dependence in a Bat‐Dispersed Species",
  "abstract": "One of the hypothesized benefits of seed dispersal is to escape density- and distance-responsive host-specific natural enemies near maternal plants. New World leaf-nosed bats create high-density seed/seedling patches beneath their feeding roosts in heterospecific plants away from maternal trees, which appears to nullify a key benefit of seed dispersal. By recording the entire post-germination population of a bat-dispersed tree species Calophyllum longifolium in a 50-ha plot on Barro Colorado Island, Panama, for three years, we found that seedling survival increased both away from conspecific adults and under bat feeding roosts, supporting the escape and directed dispersal hypotheses, respectively. These photographs illustrate the article “Resolving the paradox of clumped seed dispersal: positive density and distance dependence in a bat-dispersed species” by Anna Sugiyama, Liza S. Comita, Takashi Masaki, Richard Condit, and Stephen P. Hubbell published in Ecology. https://doi.org/10.1002/ecy.2512",
